<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-similarity" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Similarity</title>

<definition xml:id="def-similarity">
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>A,B</m> be <m>n\times n</m> matrices. We say that <m>A</m> is <term>
similar</term> to <m>B</m> if there is an invertible matrix
<m>P</m> such that <m>A=PBP^{-1}</m>. We write <m>A\sim B</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<p>
Similarity is an example of what is called an <term>equivalence relation</term>. This
means that, in the setting of the definition above, we have

<ol>

  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>A\sim A\quad</m> (<m>\sim</m> is reflexive)
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>A\sim B\implies B\sim A\quad</m> (<m>\sim</m> is symmetric)
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>A\sim B,\, B\sim C\implies A\sim C\quad</m> (<m>\sim</m> is transitive).
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ol>
We prove 3 and leave the others as an exercise. If <m>A\sim B</m> and
<m>B\sim C</m>, then there are invertible matrices <m>P</m> and <m>Q</m>
satisfying
<md>
A=PBP^{-1}\text{ and }B=QCQ^{-1}.
</md>
Then
<md>
A=PBP^{-1}=P(QCQ^{-1})P^{-1}=(PQ)C(PQ)^{-1}.
</md>
Since <m>PQ</m> is invertible, this says that <m>A\sim C</m>.
</p>

<p>
Similarity looks like an odd definition, but we care about this notion
because similarity preserves so many interesting properties of a matrix, as
we now see in the next result.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="thm-props-of-similarity">
<statement>
<p>
If <m>A\sim B</m>, then 
<ol>

  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\operatorname{det}(A)=\operatorname{det}(B)</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>A</m> is invertible <m>\iff</m> <m>B</m> is invertible. 
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>\operatorname{rank}(A)=\operatorname{rank}(B)</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>A,B</m> have the same eigenvalues.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  <m>A^m\sim B^m</m> for all <m>m\ge 0</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
  <p> 
  If <m>A</m> is invertible, <m>A^m\sim B^m</m> for all <m>m\in\Z</m>.
  </p>
  </li>
  
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p>
We prove property 4 and will the rest as an exercise.
</p>

<proof>
  <p>
We have 
<md>
<mrow>
A\sim B \implies A=PBP^{-1}\implies \det\amp(A-\lambda I) \\
\amp = \det(PBP^{-1}-\lambda I)\\
\amp = \det(PBP^{-1}-\lambda PIP^{-1})\\
\amp = \det(P(B-\lambda I)P^{-1})\\
\amp = \det(P)\det(B-\lambda I)\det(P^{-1})\\
\amp = \det(B-\lambda I),
</mrow>
</md>
and so <m>A,B</m> have the same eigenvalues. 
</p>
</proof>

<example xml:id="ex-sim-matrices">
<statement>
<p>
Are any of 
<md>
A=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 1\\0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix},\, 
B=\begin{bmatrix}2 \amp 1\\0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix},\, 
I_2=\begin{bmatrix}1 \amp 0\\0 \amp 1\end{bmatrix}
</md>
similar? 
</p>

<p>
We have <m>\det(A)=1=\det(I_2)</m> and <m>\det(B)=1</m>. So we 
see that <m>B\not\sim A</m> and <m>B\not\sim I_2</m>. 
</p>

<p>
Now assume that <m>A=PI_2P^{-1}</m>. Then <m>A=I_2</m>, which means the
only matrix similar to <m>I_2</m> is <m>I_2</m>. Hence <m>A\not\sim I_2</m>,
and so none of the matrices are similar. 
</p>
</statement>
</example>

</section>